## Domain 5: Muscle-Up Progression and Advanced Calisthenics

The ability to perform a bar muscle-up is a game-changer for high walls (6-8 feet) and obstacles that require a vertical "press-out".^1 It represents the ultimate expression of the pull-to-press transition.^25

### Technical Phases of the Muscle-Up Build

The muscle-up is not merely a strength feat; it is a technical sequence involving shoulder activation, hip pop, and a fast transition.^25

1. **Phase 1 — Explosive Pull-ups:** The athlete must develop the ability to pull the bar to the lower chest or even the hips (High Pulls).^25
2. **Phase 2 — The Hip Pop:** Utilizing an aggressive glute extension (kip) to create a moment of weightlessness, allowing the body to rotate around the bar.^25
3. **Phase 3 — The Transition:** Drills like "Russian Pushups" (transitioning from elbows to hands on the ground) and "Seated Band Pulldowns" (pulling to the hip) build the muscle memory for the switch from a pull to a press.^26
4. **Phase 4 — Jumping and Banded Reps:** Using a box to assist the initial jump or a band to support the hips allows the athlete to practice the "fast sit-up" motion required to clear the bar.^25

| Muscle-Up Drill | Objective | Focus Point |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Weighted Pull-ups | Strength Foundation | Lat activation and explosive pull^26 |
| Kip Swings | Kinetic Energy | Generating momentum through the core^25 |
| Snap to Support | Transition Timing | Moving from "hips open" to "hips closed"^29 |
| Eccentric Negatives | Control & Strength | Slow descent from the top of the bar^26 |

